body:
In Node.js' community Discord server I was told I could flush messages by appending "\n" at the end of the last socket.write, so I could potentially do:

```javascript
socket.write('hi');
socket.write(' how are ');
socket.write('you\n');
```

And that would send as "hi how are you", however, with this piece of code:

`server.js`:
```javascript
const { Server } = require('net');

new Server(socket => {
    for (let i = 0; i < 50; i++)
        socket.write('Hello\n');
})
    .on('close', () => console.log('Server closed'))
    .on('error', console.error)
    .listen(9000);
```
`client.js`:
```javascript
const { Socket } = require('net');

let messages = 0;
new Socket()
    .on('error', console.error)
    .on('connect', () => console.log('Socket connected'))
    .on('data', (buffer) => console.log(
        `Received message no ${++messages} with byte-length of ${buffer.byteLength}`))
    .on('close', (hadError) => {
        console.log('Socket closed');
        process.exit(Number(hadError));
    })
    .connect(9000);
```

The messages are sent as a single one, despite of them being sent as 50 separated messages.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24852502/47368849-b7d5df80-d6e2-11e8-93fb-8b31d1cb7311.png)

* **Version**: 10.12.0
* **Platform**: Windows 10 Home
* **Subsystem**: socket/tcp

<!-- Please provide more details below this comment. -->

text:
Socket#write does not seem to flush

In Node.js' community Discord server I was told I could flush messages by appending "\n" at the end of the last socket.write, so I could potentially do:

```javascript
socket.write('hi');
socket.write(' how are ');
socket.write('you\n');
```

And that would send as "hi how are you", however, with this piece of code:

`server.js`:
```javascript
const { Server } = require('net');

new Server(socket => {
 for (let i = 0; i < 50; i++)
 socket.write('Hello\n');
})
 .on('close', () => console.log('Server closed'))
 .on('error', console.error)
 .listen(9000);
```
`client.js`:
```javascript
const { Socket } = require('net');

let messages = 0;
new Socket()
 .on('error', console.error)
 .on('connect', () => console.log('Socket connected'))
 .on('data', (buffer) => console.log(
 `Received message no ${++messages} with byte-length of ${buffer.byteLength}`))
 .on('close', (hadError) => {
 console.log('Socket closed');
 process.exit(Number(hadError));
 })
 .connect(9000);
```

The messages are sent as a single one, despite of them being sent as 50 separated messages.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24852502/47368849-b7d5df80-d6e2-11e8-93fb-8b31d1cb7311.png)

* ** **: 10.12.0
* ** **: Windows 10 Home
* ** **: socket/tcp

